Limited temporal displacement falls far from the Sunsetter's; however, the Asuia shows promise for mass production, 'logistically feasible' even. Standard FCS and targeting requires adjustment; time dilation proves difficult to overcome without direct integration with OCTANTIS. Send the reports through to it, I'm sure it'll have a solution prepared before it arrives.

Integration trials with OCTANTIS have yielded anomalous efficiencies - flux vents cycling 15% ahead of projected timelines, as if the ship anticipates overload before it manifests. We've noted crew disorientation in sim-runs: echoes of commands issued seconds before they're spoken, shadows of maneuvers that resolve into reality. Recommend psychological conditioning protocols for deployment batches. If OCTANTIS can stabilize the dilation bubble without fracturing causality, the Asuia could redefine ambush doctrine. Fleet Admiral August has authorized Phase II prototyping under Kori's nanoforge; Tri-Tachyon liaisons are pressing for data shares, but the Office will redact temporal metrics.

// Addendum, deleted from record:
// "The latest sim-feed from OCTANTIS... It's not just predicting. The Asuia prototype engaged a Hegemony Onslaught battlegroup in the trial, but the logs show damage patterns from weapons that weren't fired until after the kill."
// "Causality bleed. We've seen it in the deep-core interfaces before - OCTANTIS pulling threads from some unknown subroutines. If we push this, we're not building ships; we're unraveling the present. August knows, doesn't he, surely?"
